  "prompt": "How pancreatic cancer is treated?",
  "response": "Pancreatic cancer treatment depends on the stage, location, and overall health of the patient. Common treatment approaches include:\n\n1. Surgery\n- Whipple procedure\n- Distal pancreatectomy\n- Total pancreatectomy\n- Removing tumors that haven't spread\n\n2. Chemotherapy\n- Drugs to kill cancer cells\n- Often used before or after surgery\n- Common drugs: gemcitabine, 5-fluorouracil\n\n3. Radiation therapy\n- High-energy radiation to destroy cancer cells\n- Can be used alone or combined with chemotherapy\n- External beam radiation or targeted radiation\n\n4. Targeted therapy\n- Drugs targeting specific cancer cell characteristics\n- Blocks cancer cell growth and spread\n\n5. Immunotherapy\n- Stimulates immune system to fight cancer cells\n- Checkpoint inhibitors\n- Clinical trials exploring new treatments\n\n6. Palliative care\n- Manages symptoms and improves quality of life\n- Pain management\n- Nutritional support\n\n7. Clinical trials\n- Experimental treatments\n- New drug combinations\n- Innovative therapies\n\nTreatment is personalized and may involve a combination of these approaches, depending on individual patient factors and cancer stage.",
